Part I - (Loan Data from Prosper)¶

by (Olorunleke Akindote-White)¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Loan Status

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Borrower APR
  • Loan Term
  • Borrower Rate
  • Lender Yield
  • Listing Category
  • Occupation
  • Employment Status
  • Employment Status Duration
  • Available Bank Card credit
  • Income range'
  • Monthly Loan repayment

#-- Loan Status in order of significance
loan_classes = ['Current','Completed', 'FinalPaymentInProgress', 'Past Due (1-15 days)', 'Past Due (16-30 days)', 
                  'Past Due (31-60 days)','Past Due (61-90 days)','Past Due (91-120 days)',
                'Past Due (>120 days)','Chargedoff', 'Defaulted','Cancelled']
if (int(pd_ver[0]) > 0) or (int(pd_ver[1]) >= 21): # v0.21 or later
    ln_classes = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = loan_classes)
    loans_sub['loanstatus'] = loans_sub['loanstatus'].astype(ln_classes)
else: # pre-v0.21
    loans_sub['loanstatus'] = loans_sub['loanstatus'].astype('category', ordered = True,categories = loan_classes)

To check for population count bias in the target variable, I have decided to express the loan status as proportions of the total.¶

In [18]:
#-- obtaining the count per loan status category in decreasing order of count
status_counts = loans_sub['loanstatus'].value_counts()
#-- obtaining the total number of status counts overall
n_status = status_counts.sum()
#-- obtaining the maximum status count
max_status_count = status_counts[0]
#-- calculating the proportions of loan status with respect to the overall population count
max_status_prop = max_status_count/n_status
status_props = np.arange(0,max_status_prop,0.05)
# plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sb.countplot('loanstatus',data=loans_sub,color=color)
locs,labels = plt.xticks(rotation=45)
for loc, label in zip(locs,labels):
    count = status_counts[label.get_text()]
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_status)
    plt.text(loc,count+2,pct_string,ha='center',color='black')
    
plt.xlabel('Loan Status')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Percentage Distribution of Profiles per Loan Status');

As can be seen, the distribution per loan status remains as it before the feature engineering and most of the loans are currenly ongoing.

We see that the three variables above share a rather similar bin interval. Therefore, to avoid code repitition, we write a function that automates the histogram plots for all three of them.¶

In [27]:
def count_func(data,xVar):
    '''This function plots a histogram depicting the distribution of a continuous 
    variable on the x-axis
    
    input: Dataframe, X-variable
    
    output: formatted histogram with title and defined bins'''
    
    # set plot dimensions
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    
    #set the bins for distribution
    bins = np.arange(0,data[str(xVar)].max()+0.01,0.01)
    
    # plot
    plt.hist(x=xVar,data=data,bins=bins)
    
    # add title to plot
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {xVar}'''.title())
    
    # add x label
    plt.xlabel(xVar.title())
    
    # add y label
    plt.ylabel('Count'.title())

Next, we call the function for all three variables and the dataframe¶

Borrower APR¶

In [28]:
count_func(loans_sub,'borrowerapr')

Borrower Rate¶

In [29]:
count_func(loans_sub,'borrowerrate')

Lender Yield¶

In [30]:
count_func(loans_sub,'lenderyield')

We see a very similar distribution for Borrower rate, Borrower APR, and Lender yield. The three distributions peak between 0.30 and 0.35

#-- making a regression plot of lender yield against borrower APR

We now confirm that all three variables represented in the scatter plots above are strongly correlated. The lender yield and borrower rate going by the histograms and scatter plots are equal in context. The yield is percentage of earnings a lender earns for lending money which translates to the eventual interest levied on the borrower. This explains the strong linear relationship between both variables. The APR differs a bit because it includes other charges representing the cost of the loan to the borrower. This explains slight deviations from the line of best fit on the scatter plots and xbins difference in the histograms.

Conclusions¶
